story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising. 1 in 2 people have cancer in their lifetime, so it's really important to support charities like MacMillan. For people living alone with cancer, MacMillan is a friend to talk to. For people getting to grips with their cancer, MacMillan is someone to explain. For people struggling to pays bills with cancer, MacMillan is a helping hand. By donating, you can be that helping hand to somebody.

Sponsor me to run 100 miles over 3 months, and your money will go to someone who needs it most.

eventName: Support MacMillan Cancer Support on World Cancer Day 2021
pageSummary: The FST and HYP are collaborating because they provide aid and support for cancer patients
pageSummaryWhat: The FST and HYP are collaborating
pageSummaryWhy: they provide aid and support for cancer patients
story:
World Cancer Day is an annual event on, 4th of February to raise awareness on cancer.¬†


It aims to inform the general public on how cancer is detected and how it can be prevented and treated. This can decrease death rates caused by cancer and an opportunity to unite on this cause.


Health Professionals for Yemen (HPY) and The Farah Saeed Trust (FST) are fundraising together for Macmillan Cancer Support as part of World Cancer Day. MacMillan Cancer Support aims to provide support to cancer patients, their families and community members in the UK through information, training, advice and research.


Health Professionals For Yemen (HPY) are a team of health professionals that support the health system in Yemen through training, education, and collaboration. Please visit their website: hpyemen.com


The Farah Saeed Trust (thefst.weebly.com) is a group of professionals who volunteer in their spare time to conduct a range of programmes and projects to inspire, educate and help within their ability. It is named after Dr Farah Saeed, an amazing person diagnosed with gastric metastatic cancer in March 2014 at the age of 27 and passed away on 8th September 2014. One of its programmes is the Farah With Me cancer project that aims to raise awareness of cancer and fundraise for cancer charities. Please visit their Farah With Me cancer project website farahwithme.weebly.com

Please support our unified cause to eliminate cancer and support the communities in the UK.

story:
It is with heavy heart that our family shares that, husband, father and grandfather, Yiannis Stylianou, passed away peacefully, at home surrounded by his wife and children on January 2nd 2021. He leaves behind his wife, Loukia, children, Steven, Andrew and Anthi, his grandchildren, Yiannis and Eirini.¬†

Yiannis was a well known and respected member of the Brighton and Greek Cypriot communities. A hardworking businessman, born into poverty, he devoted his life to helping his much-loved family and Greek community.¬†

A man of great strength and drive, he spoke of his proudest life‚Äôs
achievements to be establishing his entire family, from a small
agricultural village in Cyprus, into Brighton life and being a founding
father of the Greek Orthodox Church of the Holy Trinity, Brighton.

The Macmillan Cancer Support were very supportive.

pageSummary: Fund raising instead of funeral flowers because following mum's wishes.
pageSummaryWhat: Fund raising instead of funeral flowers
story:
Our lovely Ivy mum passed away on the 29th December 2020, just a few months short of her 94th birthdays. She died peacefully, surrounded by those she loved; her daughter Penny, son Ian and daughter-in-law Fiona.¬†

Mum led a long and largely happy life. She loved family, friends and her little bungalow garden, where she looked forward to the spring¬†flowers every year, promising the end of winter. The only shadow in her life was the death of her¬†beloved husband Alf, who died¬†of cancer 40 years ago. It is for this reason that instead of funeral flowers she asked for¬†people to donate¬†to Macmillan Cancer Support.

Although she never really got over dad's passing she did¬†her best to build a new life. At 60 she learnt to drive and at 80¬†started to grapple with computers, attending several adult education classes. Although I am sure mum would¬†be the first to admit she never quite got the hang of social media. She also¬†took up art, becoming quite accomplished at landscapes, and flower¬†arranging, receiving¬†several prizes at local shows.

However, Mum never forgot dad‚Äôs battle with cancer and how¬†frightening and isolating a diagnosis can be for the whole family. In the 1980s she became¬†one of the first Pilgrims Hospice volunteers¬† and worked tirelessly¬†for the organisation for over 20 years both at the Margate Hospice and in the Cliftonville shop. She¬†was also a strong supporter of the Macmillan nurses who had provided such comfort¬†and support to her when she was nursing dad alone at home in his final months. It is for this¬†reason we are hoping to raise funds for the charity in her memory.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Rest in peace mum. We love you. Xxx

pageSummary: Traceys 1st challenge for 2021 because I lost my friend Tracy at cancer at 40
pageSummaryWhy: I lost my friend Tracy at cancer at 40
story:
Hi everyone I really hope you will join me in helping to raise money for Macmillan Cancer Research. I sadly lost a friend of mine Tracy at 40 years of age. Due to Macmillans amazing work I also have many friends who have survived this horrendous disease.

My poem sums up how I feel and hope it inspires and encourages you to donate and help Macmillan.¬†

Cancer, Cancer,¬†

One day research will find the answer,¬†

It will no longer be a massive anchor,¬†¬†

It takes away so many, we¬†need every penny,

We must keep fighting,¬†

Keep funding,¬†

Cancer is so cunning,¬†we¬†must keep running,¬†

As fast as we can ,to stop the disease that doesn‚Äôt give a damn,¬†

It can attack any time,

woman, man, any age and any stage,¬†

We will beat it, lets get mad, not sad, it is bad,¬†

We are strong, don‚Äôt wait too long,

Fundraising is vital,¬†

Cancer is not entitled,

Lets raise awareness,¬†

Stop this unfairness,

So it no longer scares us,

Money is what research needs,

Every minute of every day,

To make this damn disease concede,

Lets get this horrific disease beat,

Cancer, Cancer, retreat, retreat.

eventName: Cycling 520km over 12months for The British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. ¬£24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks! This also counts towards my DofE Gold award Volunteering! I aim to cycle 10km a week for 12 months commencing 11/01/2021. I aim to complete 520km by the end of these 12 months, but that is my minimum, so hopefully I can do more.¬†

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. My name is Oli, I am 13 and I want to raise money for this charity as it has had much less funding over the past 12 months than usual due to the effects of Covid-19.

This is a charity close to my family's heart as Christmas 2019 my grandad had to have a double heart bypass, the doctor's said that if he hadn't been so fit and active, his heart wouldn't have coped for as long as it did - it was so strong due to his walking and cycling. But it was down to medical science and research that the doctors were able to save him and now he is fit and well.

I want to set myself a fitness challenge with a sport I am not very confident with. I have only ever run a maximum of 5km in one go, that was 8 months ago and I said I'd never do it again, so the idea of running 180km in three months is horrible and feels impossible.¬† But I will try my best!¬† If you sympathise with me, and understand my pain, please sponsor me for this amazing cause!¬†

It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. ¬£24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks, Oli :)

story:
We have created this dedicated page in the Memory of Dawn Watson who sadly passed away at home on 4th January, we know the Crematorium would have been overwhelmed with all of Dawns Family & Friends but due to the current Covid Guidelines sadly this is severely restricted to 15 people.

Dawns Family have asked for Donations to be made to British Heart Foundation, they also would like to thank everyone for their heartfelt messages of condolences and support during this very¬†difficult.

Dawn is resting Peacefully at Complete Funeral Services, Seaham 01915412373

Dawn is sadly missed by all her loving family and friends xx

story:
Due to the current circumstances and restrictions in place, we have set up a Just Giving page in memory of¬†

John Robert Commons.

We thought this would be a nice way to support a charity that he had supported for many years. Thanks to the amazing work and research done by the British Heart Foundation, we have had many years to make lasting memories with Dad. Therefore we are asking for donations in place of flowers. ¬†¬†


A little bit about the British Heart Foundation: They are the nation's heart charity. They help save lives with information, patient care, and pioneering research. With your support, we're on the way to beating heart disease for good.


~THANK YOU~

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

pageSummary: HELP ME RAISE MONEY because they need our help more than ever!
pageSummaryWhy: they need our help more than ever!
story:
Hi I‚Äôm trying to raise money how ever little it may be for this great cause, ¬†every penny will help.¬†I‚Äôve had family and friends with life threatening heart conditions . ¬†The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. It has meant devastating decisions to cut 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, the British Heart Foundation has never needed people help so much as they do now. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help them keep up the pace of progress and giving up sweets abd/or chocolate is a very small price to pay in order to make a huge difference to this wonderful cause¬†. With the Covid crisis at the forefront and so much money being ploughed into helping get the dreadful virus under control, sadly many charities for other life threatening illnesses may be effected. Please let us not forget how important this is as despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our children, mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we must not over look this. If you can spare even just as little as ¬†¬£1, I would really much appreciate this.¬†

Much Love¬†

Nicky ‚ù§Ô∏è¬†

pageSummary: I am giving up chocolate throughout March because it‚Äôs a very important charity to me
pageSummaryWhat: I am giving up chocolate throughout March
pageSummaryWhy: it‚Äôs a very important charity to me
story:
Everyone who knows me knows how much I love chocolate and my full fat, full sugar coke. However, raising money for heart charities is even more important to me.

I lost my first child, Daniel, in 2007 to a congenital heart defect, Hypoplastic Left Heart Syndrome. My uncle John also died when I was a baby, of a heart defect. As well as this, I know far too many people who are affected, either directly or indirectly, by heart issues.¬†

My darling boy was born and died in March. I‚Äôve seen this challenge several times over the years, and never felt it was something I would be able to do. However, this year, I‚Äôm determined to finally do it, and hopefully raise a little bit of money for the British Heart Foundation whilst I‚Äôm at it.

story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
I have decided that in March I will give up on chocolate and sweets, which doesn‚Äôt sound like a big deal but anyone who knows me will know how big of a challenge this is going to be 😂¬†I am going to try my best! Not only to raise money but to raise awareness around heart problems!¬†

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. pageSummary: I am doing 31 days of no chocolate in March because I want to raise money towards BHF research
pageSummaryWhat: I am doing 31 days of no chocolate in March
pageSummaryWhy: I want to raise money towards BHF research
story:
Hello,

I'm sure the majority of you know who I am, but for those that don't know me...

I am Lizzie (25yrs), girlfriend to Ben and mummy to Sienna.¬† I have a questionable relationship with chocolate, it's either a whole share bar or nothing type of thing.¬† If you know me well, you'll be reading this and thinking "she's going to struggle doing this", and the answer is YES I AM but here's why I'm doing it.

My Daddy unfortunately passed away on 1st March 2014¬† whilst my family and I were on a skiing holiday in France.¬† This was about 3 weeks after his 59th birthday.¬† He suffered from a ruptured dissecting thoracic aortic aneurysm (a mouthful, I know).¬† I would be surprised if you knew what that is so there's a link at the bottom for more info.¬† One day he was here, the next morning he was gone.¬† He left a massive hole in everyone's lives that knew him, especially mine.¬† He was my hero, my best friend but most of all my Daddy.¬† After 7 years I still can't believe he's gone.

I haven't done anything charity wise for him since he died as I haven't managed to pluck up the courage to share my story.¬† It's never something I've spoken about to anyone.¬† 2021 feels like the right year to be brave and jump into something crazy (for me that is).¬†¬†

Any donations or even messages of support would be massively appreciated.¬† I really want to raise awareness about my story and help British Heart Foundation in their research of heart and circulatory diseases.

Lots of love

Lizzie xx

P.S Thank you very much in advance ‚ù§¬†

https://www.bhf.org.uk/informationsupport/conditions/aortic-aneurysm

story: The pandemic is the biggest challenge the BHF have faced in their 60 year history. And it's led to them being forced to make the devastating decision to cut their 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, they have never needed fundraising more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help the BHF keep up the pace of progress. Your donation will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need it most. Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now. Loosing my dad in 2018 from heart disease means this fundraising has an extra special meaning to me and I want to do my best to raise as much as I can for the BHF and their vital research so others don't have to go through the same pain of loosing a loved one. I am going to do this challenge for the months of February AND March in the hope that everyone I know can donate even a tiny amount to help me reach my target. Thank you all so much for your support 💝

story:
In loving memory of Trixie Ponder¬†

In these strange times where we cannot meet we would invite you to share memories and tributes to our lovely Mum, Nan and Great Nan.

Trixie brought joy and love to so many people, not only was she caring and loving to her family but Trixie shared her big heart through her work.

Working with children at Black Notely nursery school, William Julian and Black Notely hospital.¬†

Please feel free to email any pictures you have with Trixie so that we can add them to her page, we would love to see them jodypudney@hotmail.com

Trixie will be greatly missed by all.¬†

pageSummary: We decided to push ourselves and walk the peaks because each of us in some way has been impacted by Cancer
pageSummaryWhat: We decided to push ourselves and walk the peaks
pageSummaryWhy: each of us in some way has been impacted by Cancer
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

This all began as an accident!

With 2020 being such a crazy year, trying to exercise has simply been a challenge, gyms open, gyms closed etc etc...

Back in June/July I was walking an average of 3 miles a day. ¬†All locally and all generally on flat ground. ¬†In October we moved house close to the edge of the Peak District, the views are simply amazing... ¬†That said, the walking had pretty much stopped.

With a keen set of brother in laws, we decided to start up our walking again and accidentally found ourselves walking between 3 and 4 miles up some fairly steep hills in December.

Since then, we have grown more and more confident with our walks and have now decided to push our boundaries. by climbing¬†the UK's three highest peaks. ¬†At present we are walking between 8 and 10 miles each time and climbing 2/3rds of the heights required for Ben Nevis - the tallest of the 3 peaks.

We thought instead of us just walking for the sake of walking, why not let our efforts do some good!

So, over the coming months we will work on training to walk the peaks and once able (owing to the various lockdowns and current Covid situation), we will make our attempts.

Please do donate generously so we can provide a little assistance to those truly in need and hopefully assist in finding a cure for this life changing illness.


Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

pageSummary: I am walking virtually because in memory of Gary Hart
story:
As some of you know, I worked in Saudi Arabia, on and off, for 10 years.

Gary was my friend Tracy's brother and we used to go out and about together socially.¬† Gary worked for BAE in Saudi, whilst myself and Tracy worked at Aramco.

Gary and his family moved from Cornwall, UK, to Australia, in his younger years, but always kept his UK roots and supported Liverpool Football Club.¬† As he was from Cornwall, I thought it appropriate to do my walk in his memory, being as I started from Lands End.

Gary moved back to Australia, from Saudi, a few years ago.¬† He became ill, just over a year ago and sadly lost his fight against cancer, just after Christmas.

I will be thinking of Gary, Tracy, Val and Chris whilst I do my steps.¬† Gary loved sport too (touch football) so I am sure he will be cheering me on in spirit.

Back in 2019, a new modern-day fictional hero of ‚ÄúGrabber‚Äù entered the book world titled "Lots of Middle Names".¬†Grabber¬†is the antithesis of your typical fictional hero, he is interested only in solving low-level fraud (think shortchanging innocent customers, or people evading paying for their TV license, or other such crimes!).¬†¬†Grabber¬†tries to avoid physical conflict and is armed only with a solar-powered calculator and his quick(ish) thinking, but he will get to the bottom of whatever low-level financial crime is put in front of him - most of the time anyway.¬†

The successful release of this original Grabber thriller "Lots of Middle Names" raised over ¬£1000 for Cancer Research UK.¬† During the 2020-21 lockdown(s), charities have suffered in terms of donations and Jennifer and Jonathan felt the release of Grabber would in some small way, help: both the avid Grabber fans and Cancer Research UK.

pageSummary: In loving memory of our Mamma because of excellent care whilst in hospice
pageSummaryWhat: In loving memory of our Mamma
pageSummaryWhy: of excellent care whilst in hospice
story:
We lost our Mamma on 7th January 2021 after a short illness and she was admitted to Marie Curie Hospice in Hampstead for end of life care. In her final days the whole team at the hospice was very caring and made her very comfortable ¬†The doctors and nurses were excellent and were there not only for our mum but for family members as well.

We've been caring for people with serious illnesses in Barnet, Brent, Camden, Enfield, Haringey and Islington for more than 60 years, now.Every single day at the hospice is an extraordinary day. And every moment is precious. Our hospice nurses, doctors and therapists provide the best possible care for people with serious illnesses, and offer vital emotional support for them and their families. The hospice is a warm, welcoming place where loved ones can be together in peaceful surroundings and in as much comfort as possible. Whether it's for one day or several weeks, the time people spend at the hospice is precious, and is cherished by them and their families.Thank you for supporting us, and helping to make sure more people with a terminal illness in North London get the care and support they need."When I was admitted, I was confined to a wheelchair, in constant pain. Now I walk between five and seven miles a day. You can see how good Marie Curie is in that I walk" - Matthew

eventName: UK 3 Peaks Challenge with University of Reading
story:
Hello and welcome!
On the 15th June I'm going to be doing the UK 3 Peaks Challenge with the University of Reading in aid of¬†Marie Curie.
We have to climb Ben Nevis, Scafell Pike and Mount Snowdon, all in the space of 36 hours. It's a 25 mile hike in total, and we will be climbing over 5,200 feet.
It's going to be tough but I am so excited to do something good for such an important cause.
I need to raise at least ¬£680 by the end of April to be able to complete the challenge, and it's going to a really fantastic charity that does incredible work and provides vital care and support for those who are terminally ill and their families.
I will be doing several other fundraising challenges in the lead-up to the challenge:

A 36 hour fast in January (to match the time period of the challenge)
Running 25 miles per week in February (to match the miles we will trek)
2500 burpees throughout March (to match the feet we will climb)
A 680 minute walk in April (to match my fundraising target)
I will be documenting these as well as my training/prep as much as possible to keep it fun and also prove that I'm serious about completing the challenge.
I understand that times such as this are tough for all of us for varying reasons, but any donations you may be able to spare would be so greatly appreciated.

Dot was always a family person for all of her 95 years of her life. Always laughing and joking making memories that we will all never forget. She was always fun bubbly person to be around which will all loved and we miss her so much. From the memories we have that will never go away, like when we used to go round and she would turn her hearing aids down so she couldn‚Äôt hear us to making us laugh from the things she came out with.¬†

When dot became end of life Marie curie step in to help us as a family to give us the time and break we needed by staying over night, watching her and treating her as one of their own. Marie curie are an amazing charity who relay on donations of the public to keep it running, this is why we want to raise as much money as we can, so they can carry on helping other family‚Äôs doing the great job they do just like they did with us.¬†

Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

pageSummary: I am joining Reading Uni's fundraising effort because charities need help more than ever at this time.
pageSummaryWhat: I am joining Reading Uni's fundraising effort
pageSummaryWhy: charities need help more than ever at this time.
story:
Thank you for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

In June this year, I will be taking part in the Three Peaks Challenge - a trek to summit three of the tallest mountains in the United Kingdom (Ben Nevis, Scafell Pike and Mount Snowdon) - in order to raise money for the fantastic Marie Curie charity.¬†Myself and a team of people from the University of Reading, in conjunction with the tour provider 'Choose A Challenge',¬†will walk 25 miles and climb over 5,200 feet in just 36 hours. Throughout the year, I will be training, fundraising, and keeping up to date with all the wonderful work being done by Marie Curie.

The impact of the coronavirus pandemic has been devastating across all sectors over the past year, and it's more important than ever to support our charities. Marie Curie offers invaluable care, guidance and comfort to those living with any terminal illness, as well as supporting families through the most difficult times. I am humbled to be raising money for such a meaningful cause, and would be so grateful for any help and donations along the way. For more information about the charity, please follow the link below:

story:
RNLI means a lot to me, I mean it has to right, ive got a RNLI wellie tattooed on me.

I am walking 2 miles a day in February to help raise money, with covid shutting their shops they have really lost a lot of donations!¬†

2 miles a day may not seem a lot to some but for me its a massive feat i am struggling to walk due to various reasons and most days I don't even get dressed. By doing this every day I'm hoping to lose some weight why not, and also be mentally better in myself. So please donate ¬£1 or ¬£10 itll all go towards my favourite charity!

I would love to raise enough for 2 thermal vests ¬£50 each.

Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI‚Äôs help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They‚Äôre the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.Thank you.

pageSummary: We are taking on Mile an Hour challenge because we are passionate environmentalists (not runners).
pageSummaryWhat: We are taking on Mile an Hour challenge
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page!

Our challenge:¬†13 miles, 13 hours and most likely countless bags of litter.

On the 13/02/21, to raise some money for the incredible World Wildlife Fund, we will be running a mile an hour for 13 hours; the equivalent of a half marathon. In between each of these miles for the remainder of the hour we will be litter picking across the length of our coastline; and there is unfortunately more than enough to keep us occupied!¬†

We are excited to be able to hit all these locations all in one day, as through our litter picking group- Litterless Leigh- we often want to do more.

Our motivation: The natural world and system is in need of desperate support, a reality we see so clearly in our local environment Southend-on-Sea, which despite the views is in desperate need of TLC. Taking on this challenge combines these two ideas through cleaning up our local environment and providing financial support to a charity which can provide widespread positive impact.

pageSummary: I pledge to walk 100 miles in a month because I'm usually a festival steward for Oxfam!
pageSummaryWhat: I pledge to walk 100 miles in a month
pageSummaryWhy: I'm usually a festival steward for Oxfam!
story:
As a dedicated Oxfam festival steward, I can usually take for granted that my summer will be filled with amazing times, lots of fun and fundraising for Oxfam! Sadly Covid 19 means that this didn't happen in 2020 and 2021 isn't looking so certain either!

So I want to make a difference how I can. I'm going to walk 100 miles between now and my birthday - whether I have to pace around the living room or take myself on challenging walks. There will also be some invigorating cold-water dips and swims involved. I'll be adding distance swum onto my target!

This is why I'm raising money for Oxfam!

Climate change is affecting millions of the worlds poorest people, right now. More frequent and extreme weather is destroying homes, and wrecking lives. The people who have done the least to cause the climate emergency are being hit the hardest this is an injustice that can and must be stopped.Oxfam is protecting families forced to flee their homes, supporting those hit by changing weather, making sure children have a chance of a future free from poverty and responding to the deadly threat of coronavirus. Through all of this, we rely on brilliant supporters like you to make sure our dedicated teams can be where they're needed most. We couldn't do our work without you.Every donation, no matter how big or small, makes a difference. Together, we won't live with poverty.

pageSummary: 100km in under 30 hours along the South Downs Way because I want to help end poverty and improve lives
pageSummaryWhat: 100km in under 30 hours along the South Downs Way
pageSummaryWhy: I want to help end poverty and improve lives
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Here we go again to prepare for our deferred covid impacted 2020 entry!¬†A combination of unfinished business and enjoyment for the 2019 event has meant that I‚Äôm back to try and once again conquer the mighty South Downs.¬†

The 2019 team completed the event in just over 23hrs - with a revised focus of a sub 20hr time 💪🏽.

Joining me is¬†fellow 2019 team member Adrian¬†Pinnock who wants again leads the team along with two new fresh and hungry walkers of¬†Nick Dixon¬†and Ben Locke.

Together we become the third reincarnation of the original 2017 team; Rochefort Four Vol 3.1 (3.0 is the 2020 Covid impacted team that never saw the hills!)

In the vitally important support crew role are Martyn Lillywhite and Owen Kenny.

So how can you help? We need to raise ¬£1400 as a team just ¬£350 a member so I would massively appreciate it if you could reach into your pockets and help me out 🙏🏽

The Charity

Trailwalker is the endurance challenge of a lifetime. Around 500 teams of 4 will take on 100km of the South Downs Way in September. All the while, helping to end poverty with each step. The money raised will be used by Oxfam and The Gurkha Welfare Trust to improve lives around the world.

Oxfam is a movement of millions of people, all working towards one goal - an end to poverty to everyone. In over 70 years we've become world leaders in emergency water and sanitation, and experts in providing shelter, food and protection.

¬†The Gurkha Welfare Trust provide financial, medical and development aid to Gurkha veterans, their families and communities in Nepal as well as welfare advice to the UK Gurkha Community.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

THANK YOU & Namaste.

charity.name: Unicef UK
story: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. Today, children in places like Syria, South Sudan and Yemen are caught up in violent conflict, with millions forced to flee their homes. Please donate what ever you can to my fundraiser for Unicef UK. With your help, we can build a safer world for children.  For more information d visit www.unicef.org.uk
